body:
@nmnobre has found that PSyclone generates incorrect OMP parallel code in NEMO's `icedyn_rhg_evp` module:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17409212/217834473-c5831861-a33f-46ef-9b60-e59a4bba1aa9.png)

In this case, if `ln_aEVP` is `.false.` then every thread will need the value of `z1_alph2` that is assigned before the loop. i.e. `z1_alph2` needs to be `firstprivate` and not `private`.

Whilst working on PR #792 it became apparent that that the logic for `write_args` Fortran intent in `    `Invoke.unique_declns_by_intent` is not quite correct. We have
```
        # sum_args behave as if they are write_args from
        # the PSy-layer's perspective.
        write_args += sum_args
        # readwrite_args behave in the same way as inc_args
        # from the perspective of first access and intents
        inc_args += readwrite_args
```
and then there are first checks for "inc" and "readwrite" args 
```
        for arg in inc_args:
            ...
            first_arg = self.first_access(arg.declaration_name)
            if first_arg.access != AccessType.WRITE:
                if arg not in declns["inout"]:
                    declns["inout"].append(arg)
            else:
                if arg not in declns["out"]:
                    declns["out"].append(arg)
```
and after that for "pure" writers
```
        for arg in write_args:
            # For every argument that is written to by at least one kernel,
            # identify the type of the first access - if it is read
            # or inc'd before it is written then it must have intent(inout).
            # However, we deal with inc and readwrite args separately so we
            # do not consider those here.
            first_arg = self.first_access(arg.declaration_name)
            if first_arg.access == AccessType.READ:
                if arg not in declns["inout"]:
                    declns["inout"].append(arg)
            else:
                if arg not in declns["out"]:
                    declns["out"].append(arg)
```
However, **there is a possibility that a "write" arg can have a  "read"-like first access access other than `AccessType.READ`** so the check should be something like
```
        for arg in write_args:
            ...
            first_arg = self.first_access(arg.declaration_name)
            if first_arg.access in (AccessType.READ, AccessType.READWRITE, AccessType.INC):
                if arg not in declns["inout"]:
                    declns["inout"].append(arg)
            else:
                if arg not in declns["out"]:
                    declns["out"].append(arg)
```
This would prevent having an Invoke argument with an incorrect `intent(out)` instead of the correct `intent(inout)` if previously it had a "read" access.
